WEBVTT

00:01.043 --> 00:04.923
WARGRAVE:
U.N. Owen...is "unknown."

00:05.047 --> 00:07.891
BLORE: We must all have
something in common,

00:08.007 --> 00:09.225
someone who knows us all.

00:09.343 --> 00:10.720
It's the poem.

00:10.844 --> 00:12.221
It's the poem.
Don't you see?

00:12.346 --> 00:13.814
MacARTHUR:
No one's coming for us.

00:13.931 --> 00:15.057
This is the end.

00:15.182 --> 00:17.355
CYRIL:
You like Uncle Hugo, don't you?

00:17.476 --> 00:18.477
VERA:
I do.

00:18.602 --> 00:19.979
I'm in love with him.

00:20.103 --> 00:21.446
DR. ARMSTRONG:
One chopped himself in half,

00:21.563 --> 00:22.780
and then there were six.

00:22.898 --> 00:24.571
So she's right.
It is the poem.

00:24.691 --> 00:26.443
We have sharp minds.

00:27.027 --> 00:28.495
We should stay together.

00:28.612 --> 00:30.910
PHILIP:
It was locked,

00:31.031 --> 00:33.284
which means there must be
a master key.

00:33.408 --> 00:35.831
BLORE: Any one of us
could have had the key.

00:35.953 --> 00:38.081
Any one of us
could have the gun.

00:38.205 --> 00:40.003
WARGRAVE:
The killer is not out there.

00:40.666 --> 00:42.543
The killer is in here.

00:43.126 --> 00:44.503
It is one of us.

00:44.628 --> 00:47.802
[ Dramatic music plays]

00:49.000 --> 00:55.074
Advertise your product or brand here
contact www.OpenSubtitles.org today

01:47.190 --> 01:50.535
[Wind whistling, rain falling]

02:00.287 --> 02:02.790
[Thunder rumbling ]

02:06.043 --> 02:08.044
[Thunder crashes]

02:27.522 --> 02:30.071
OLIVIA:
Look how happy Cyril is now.

02:30.192 --> 02:32.911
Hugo always works wonders.

02:33.028 --> 02:35.281
He is the most marvelous man.

02:35.405 --> 02:37.624
VERA:
He seems very nice.

02:38.200 --> 02:40.328
I really can't imagine
many would be as kind

02:40.452 --> 02:42.204
under the circumstances.

02:42.329 --> 02:43.831
What circumstances?

02:44.915 --> 02:48.886
Well, I had no idea I was
pregnant when my husband died.

02:49.002 --> 02:51.676
So Hugo, as the nephew,
stood to inherit.

02:52.255 --> 02:53.848
And when little Cyril
popped out,

02:53.965 --> 02:55.433
that was it for Hugo's hopes.

02:55.550 --> 02:56.676
[ Chuckles ]

02:56.802 --> 03:00.727
What he needs is some rich girl
loaded down with Daddy's money.

03:00.847 --> 03:03.100
But he's a romantic.

03:03.225 --> 03:05.068
Wants to marry for love.

03:05.185 --> 03:07.984
But how can he
when he doesn't have a penny?

03:08.105 --> 03:12.451
Love, Miss Claythorne,
is a very costly pursuit.

03:12.567 --> 03:14.535
Oh!
Well done, Cyril!

03:14.653 --> 03:17.748
Oh!
[ Laughs]

03:18.365 --> 03:19.912
I might go and play with them.

03:24.871 --> 03:26.464
Ah!
Hello.

03:27.082 --> 03:29.585
Looks like we've got
some reinforcements, Cyril.

03:30.210 --> 03:31.678
Ready, old thing?

03:31.795 --> 03:32.671
CYRIL:
Ready?

03:32.796 --> 03:34.924
I don't think Miss Claythorne
can hit a ball.

03:35.048 --> 03:37.301
- Girls can't, Uncle Hugo.
- HUGO: Oh. We'll have to see.

03:39.636 --> 03:41.513
Oh!
A shot!

03:42.180 --> 03:44.399
Over here!
Quick! Quick!

03:44.516 --> 03:45.813
Quick! She's gonna get
all the way around.

03:45.934 --> 03:46.810
Come on, now.

03:46.935 --> 03:49.233
[ Laughs]

03:49.354 --> 03:50.901
Well done.

03:51.022 --> 03:52.114
Almost.

03:58.697 --> 04:01.291
DR. ARMSTRONG: We can't
just sit here doing nothing.

04:01.408 --> 04:02.785
What are we supposed to do?

04:02.909 --> 04:05.788
Light a fire on the headland.
Signal for help.

04:05.912 --> 04:07.209
PHILIP:
Not in this weather.

04:07.330 --> 04:09.674
[ Sighs]
Where's she going?

04:09.791 --> 04:11.213
Where you going?!

04:11.334 --> 04:13.052
To make tea.

04:13.170 --> 04:14.342
I'll bring it in.

04:14.463 --> 04:15.965
What else are you gonna
bring in?

04:16.089 --> 04:17.341
A knife from the kitchen?

04:17.466 --> 04:19.184
The gun from wherever
you've hidden it?

04:19.301 --> 04:21.769
And what are you gonna be
putting in the tea?

04:21.887 --> 04:23.230
She's gonna wipe out
all four of us.

04:23.346 --> 04:25.724
VERA:
There'll be lemon in the tea.

04:25.849 --> 04:28.898
I-I won't bring a knife,
and I don't have the gun.

04:29.019 --> 04:30.646
Even if I did,
I wouldn't be killing you all

04:30.771 --> 04:32.444
-at the same time, would I?
- How do we know that?

04:32.564 --> 04:35.067
Because it's one by one
and in a particular way.

04:35.192 --> 04:36.614
Or have you not been
paying attention?

04:36.735 --> 04:39.329
And nowhere on that does it say
anything about a gun,

04:39.446 --> 04:41.619
does it,
you idiotic, cretinous bastard?

04:41.740 --> 04:43.708
PHILIP:
[ Chuckles, claps hands]

04:45.243 --> 04:46.415
I'll come with you.

04:46.536 --> 04:48.413
No.

04:48.997 --> 04:53.173
No.
We go singly or in a group.

04:53.293 --> 04:56.172
[Thunder crashing ]

05:00.091 --> 05:02.435
I hear you were one
for the black square

05:02.552 --> 05:04.896
and the rope, Judge Wargrave.

05:06.681 --> 05:09.275
When it was appropriate, yes.

05:09.392 --> 05:10.939
And Tubs here tells me

05:11.061 --> 05:14.281
you used to go and watch
all the hangings you'd ordered.

05:14.397 --> 05:15.614
Is that true?

05:15.732 --> 05:17.609
You really want to stop
calling me that.

05:17.734 --> 05:19.577
Is that true, Judge?

05:21.613 --> 05:24.742
I had the power to condemn men
and women to death

05:24.866 --> 05:26.709
for their crimes.

05:27.452 --> 05:31.002
With great power comes
great responsibility.

05:31.706 --> 05:35.131
I believe that to look away
<i>as</i> that power is exercised

05:35.252 --> 05:39.132
was both irresponsible
and cowardly.

05:41.383 --> 05:43.681
Did you watch Edward Seton hang?

05:48.056 --> 05:50.900
VERA: I remember Edward Seton
from the newspapers.

05:51.977 --> 05:54.105
Everyone said he was innocent.

05:55.522 --> 05:57.069
He wasn't.

05:57.190 --> 05:59.613
He left diaries.

05:59.734 --> 06:03.034
They proved a warped
and corrupted mind.

06:03.613 --> 06:05.866
He believed his victims
were full of filth

06:05.991 --> 06:09.541
and that he was cleansing
the world of their stain.

06:10.328 --> 06:16.882
Taunting the police with clues
and misdirections excited him

06:17.002 --> 06:19.846
<i>as</i> much as torture and sadism.

06:19.963 --> 06:23.263
He was guilty, and you passed
the right verdict.

06:23.383 --> 06:24.976
Why didn't you go and see him?

06:25.802 --> 06:27.179
I did.

06:29.431 --> 06:31.433
It was unsettling.

06:32.017 --> 06:33.610
Different.

06:35.937 --> 06:38.315
He refused the hood.

06:39.232 --> 06:41.951
He wanted me to see his face.

06:42.736 --> 06:45.956
Perhaps to impute there was
some commonality between us,

06:46.072 --> 06:49.622
perhaps to...laugh at me.

06:49.743 --> 06:51.711
VERA:
Laugh at you?

06:51.828 --> 06:53.205
<i>WARGRAVE:
Yes.</i>

06:54.289 --> 06:56.462
At justice.

06:57.918 --> 07:00.216
It meant nothing to him.

07:01.212 --> 07:04.136
He wasn't cowed by it or by me.

07:05.342 --> 07:07.185
I was nothing.

07:08.136 --> 07:11.686
I would soon be forgotten,
a footnote in history.

07:13.183 --> 07:17.404
Whereas he, with his legacy
of blood and horror,

07:17.520 --> 07:19.693
would be remembered forever.

07:22.317 --> 07:24.160
Well, it worked.

07:26.821 --> 07:28.869
He haunts me still.

07:33.203 --> 07:36.252
But...laughter or not,

07:36.373 --> 07:39.252
justice came,
<i>as</i> it always does.

07:39.376 --> 07:40.923
[Thunder rumbling ]

07:41.044 --> 07:45.515
And the world is free
of his terrible darkness.

08:01.356 --> 08:02.733
DR. ARMSTRONG:
This is ridiculous.

08:02.857 --> 08:05.280
I mean, we can't just sit around
doing nothing.

08:05.402 --> 08:07.655
WARGRAVE:
Very well, Doctor.

08:09.364 --> 08:12.163
We said singly or in a group.

08:13.034 --> 08:15.287
I'm going to read.

08:15.412 --> 08:21.010
I'm sorry, Dr. Armstrong, but
your agitation tires me greatly.

08:23.420 --> 08:25.422
[ Door closes]

08:35.265 --> 08:37.438
[Thunder crashes]

08:37.558 --> 08:40.732
[ High-pitched chiming ]

08:48.862 --> 08:51.536
PHILIP:
“Justice came.“

08:51.656 --> 08:54.956
The killer and Wargrave
having common cause --

08:55.076 --> 08:59.172
the same thrill
from handing out death.

08:59.289 --> 09:01.462
You took the piss
when I said the judge --

09:01.583 --> 09:04.086
PHILIP: Yes.
Well, now I think different.

09:04.210 --> 09:06.838
How many men has he seen dangle?

09:06.963 --> 09:09.261
What does that do to someone?

09:09.382 --> 09:10.599
BLORE:
He's on his own.

09:11.593 --> 09:13.345
Could be plotting anything.

09:13.470 --> 09:15.643
[Chiming continues]

09:23.730 --> 09:26.279
[ Birds chirping ]

09:37.118 --> 09:39.462
[Chiming continues]

09:40.038 --> 09:41.506
DR. ARMSTRONG:
Stop it, will you?!

09:41.623 --> 09:43.751
Just stop it!

09:43.875 --> 09:45.218
[Chiming stops]

09:45.335 --> 09:48.134
[Rain falling]

09:48.254 --> 09:51.758
[Chiming resumes]

09:54.636 --> 09:56.809
As if we haven't had to put up
with you.

09:56.930 --> 09:59.683
Breathing and smoking.

09:59.808 --> 10:03.529
Scratching, fidgeting,
and pacing.

10:03.645 --> 10:05.488
[Chiming stops]

10:05.605 --> 10:07.357
I'm going to bed.

10:09.567 --> 10:11.820
Singly or in a group.

10:12.529 --> 10:14.998
You can watch me go up
the stairs.

10:35.885 --> 10:38.479
[Thunder crashes]

10:38.596 --> 10:40.894
[Wind whistling]

10:51.776 --> 10:53.824
[ Door closes]

10:55.363 --> 10:58.287
[ Matches rattling ]

11:05.540 --> 11:07.793
[ Exhales deeply]

11:10.336 --> 11:12.805
[Water running]

11:16.217 --> 11:19.221
[ Birds chirping in distance]

11:23.725 --> 11:25.727
[Thunder crashes]

11:35.195 --> 11:37.289
[ Door rattling ]

11:43.203 --> 11:44.625
[ Screaming ]

11:54.881 --> 11:56.349
Cyril!

11:57.634 --> 11:59.227
Cyril!

12:02.347 --> 12:04.566
Cyril!
No!

12:04.682 --> 12:06.980
[ Sobbing ]
No!

12:11.773 --> 12:13.696
No!

12:13.816 --> 12:15.033
[ Sobs ]

12:17.403 --> 12:20.077
No!

12:21.449 --> 12:22.325
MAN:
Vera?

12:22.450 --> 12:24.202
[Thunder rumbling ]

12:24.327 --> 12:25.579
Hey.

12:28.122 --> 12:29.544
Vera.

12:34.045 --> 12:34.921
- Here.
- Hold on.

12:35.046 --> 12:37.265
Oh, for Christ's sake.
It's <i>sal</i> volatile.

12:37.382 --> 12:38.474
Smelling salt.

12:38.591 --> 12:41.094
Breathe slowly in through the
nose, out through the mouth.

12:41.219 --> 12:43.017
[ Gasps, coughs]

12:43.137 --> 12:44.639
There we are.

12:44.764 --> 12:47.142
[ Breathing heavily]

12:47.267 --> 12:50.271
[Thunder rumbling,
wind whistling]

12:51.271 --> 12:54.525
These -- I thought there was
somebody in the room with me.

12:58.528 --> 13:01.532
Here.
Have some brandy.

13:01.656 --> 13:03.374
[ Gasps ]

13:03.491 --> 13:05.084
PHILIP:
[Chuckles]

13:06.661 --> 13:07.878
Good for you, Vera.

13:08.621 --> 13:11.591
What, you think
I've done something to it?

13:11.708 --> 13:13.426
PHILIP: I'm going to go
and fetch another bottle

13:13.543 --> 13:14.965
that <i>hasn't</i> been opened.

13:17.255 --> 13:19.132
I need some water.

13:19.257 --> 13:22.181
This brandy's all right.
I haven't done anything to it.

13:22.302 --> 13:24.396
Brandy's good for shock.
That's why I got it.

13:24.512 --> 13:27.015
[Whispering ]
He called her Vera.

13:27.140 --> 13:29.859
Lombard.
That's the second time.

13:29.976 --> 13:32.695
There's something going on
between them.

13:32.812 --> 13:34.689
[ Footsteps approaching ]

13:34.814 --> 13:38.489
Sealed and untampered with.

13:44.157 --> 13:46.751
-[ Thunder crashes]
- BLORE: What's that for?

13:47.327 --> 13:48.624
I don't know.

13:48.745 --> 13:50.372
BLORE:
A chandelier, maybe.

13:50.496 --> 13:51.964
Like downstairs.

13:52.081 --> 13:54.049
A chandelier?
In the bedroom?

13:54.167 --> 13:56.340
Well, it's posh people,
isn't it?

13:56.461 --> 13:58.179
They'd put a chandelier
anywhere.

13:58.296 --> 14:01.345
Put a chandelier in a pigsty
if the fancy took them.

14:01.466 --> 14:03.468
[ Laughter]

14:06.429 --> 14:08.352
I'm becoming very fond of you,
Tubs.

14:08.473 --> 14:09.520
BLORE:
Mm.

14:09.640 --> 14:11.438
You're an arrogant arsehole,
you.

14:11.559 --> 14:12.560
Ooh.

14:12.685 --> 14:14.403
Bloody hell.
Sorry, Miss Claythorne.

14:14.520 --> 14:15.612
VERA:
No. You're right.

14:15.730 --> 14:18.700
[ Laughing ]
He's an arsehole.

14:20.777 --> 14:22.575
Where's the judge?

14:22.695 --> 14:25.073
[Thunder crashes]

14:25.198 --> 14:27.371
[Wind whistling]

14:32.205 --> 14:33.707
<i>Jesus.</i>

14:42.507 --> 14:44.305
He's been shot in the head.

14:44.425 --> 14:46.427
[Thunder crashes]

14:48.471 --> 14:50.018
VERA:
What are you doing?

14:50.139 --> 14:52.983
His head needs to be wrapped
if we're gonna move him.

14:53.101 --> 14:54.273
PHILIP:
He's right.

14:54.394 --> 14:57.238
We don't want his brains
spilling out all over the floor.

14:57.814 --> 14:59.236
Don't use your jacket,
Armstrong.

14:59.357 --> 15:01.280
I'll find something else.

15:04.153 --> 15:05.621
VERA:
Shot?

15:06.489 --> 15:07.536
Are you sure?

15:07.657 --> 15:09.284
Well, look at him.

15:10.368 --> 15:13.372
We searched everywhere
for that gun.

15:15.123 --> 15:16.625
[Thunder crashes]

15:42.358 --> 15:45.362
[ Hinges creak, door closes]

15:45.486 --> 15:47.955
You went back downstairs
to get the bottle.

15:48.072 --> 15:51.622
You went downstairs, too,
to get a glass of brandy.

15:52.201 --> 15:54.499
And you.
You disappeared for a bit.

15:54.620 --> 15:57.794
To fetch my bag so that I could
attend to...Vera.

15:57.915 --> 15:59.462
We didn't hear the shot.

15:59.584 --> 16:01.552
You could have muffled it
with a cushion.

16:01.669 --> 16:03.171
Well, we'll have to take
your word for it.

16:03.296 --> 16:04.593
I've never shot a man
in the head.

16:04.714 --> 16:06.432
That's more your field
of expertise.

16:06.549 --> 16:09.393
PHILIP: How would I have had
the time to go downstairs,

16:09.510 --> 16:10.807
grab a bottle of brandy,

16:10.928 --> 16:13.556
quickly put a slug in Wargrave,
making sure that nobody heard,

16:13.681 --> 16:16.525
and dress him up
and make it back upstairs again?

16:16.642 --> 16:17.985
Tubs here was away for longer.

16:18.102 --> 16:20.525
I'm not as quick on my feet
<i>as</i> you.

16:20.646 --> 16:22.614
DR. ARMSTRONG: “Five little
soldier boys going in for law.

16:22.732 --> 16:25.235
One got Chancery,
and then there were four.“

16:26.068 --> 16:29.823
One by one...
and in a particular way.

16:29.947 --> 16:31.324
And where's my gun?

16:31.449 --> 16:33.292
Well, don't bloody look at me.

16:33.409 --> 16:35.662
DR. ARMSTRONG:
Or me.

16:40.625 --> 16:42.923
[ Footsteps approaching ]

16:49.050 --> 16:51.178
[Thunder crashes]

16:51.302 --> 16:53.805
[Wind whistling]

17:06.317 --> 17:08.786
DR. ARMSTRONG: I can't stand
the sound of that wind.

17:11.280 --> 17:13.123
I can't stand it.

17:14.242 --> 17:17.337
I'm not just gonna sit here
and wait to die.

17:17.453 --> 17:21.708
[ Mid-tempo music plays]

17:26.127 --> 17:28.550
[ Laughter in distance]

17:28.673 --> 17:32.052
In the war,
we did this all the time!

17:32.176 --> 17:34.395
[ Music continues]

17:34.512 --> 17:36.230
And stay awake!

17:36.889 --> 17:40.519
Bodies! Bodies! Bodies!
Bodies!

17:40.643 --> 17:43.442
Bones! Blood!
Skulls!

17:43.563 --> 17:46.817
Just this -- this -- this --
this parade!

17:46.941 --> 17:51.287
Endless parade of shattered --
shattered meats!

17:51.404 --> 17:56.786
Just standing there,
cutting off legs and arms and...

17:56.909 --> 18:00.664
guts everywhere
and bodies and screaming!

18:00.788 --> 18:04.008
[ Music continues]

18:05.918 --> 18:08.216
[ Laughter echoing ]

18:09.046 --> 18:13.927
MAN ON LOUDSPEAKER: Ladies
and gentlemen, silence, please.

18:14.510 --> 18:18.265
You are charged
with the following indictments.

18:18.389 --> 18:20.312
Edward George Armstrong...

18:20.433 --> 18:21.480
That's me!
[ Laughs]

18:21.601 --> 18:24.070
MAN ON LOUDSPEAKER: ...that you
murdered Louisa Mary Clees.

18:24.186 --> 18:25.688
William Henry Blore.

18:25.813 --> 18:26.735
Yeah.
That's me.

18:26.856 --> 18:29.860
MAN ON LOUDSPEAKER: ...that you
did murder James Steven Landor.

18:29.984 --> 18:31.782
- Well...
-[ Music continues]

18:31.902 --> 18:33.529
MAN ON LOUDSPEAKER:
Vera Elizabeth Claythorne...

18:33.654 --> 18:35.031
The smell!

18:35.156 --> 18:37.250
And the noise! The noise.
The noise. The noise.

18:37.366 --> 18:40.415
[Howling]

18:40.536 --> 18:42.459
[ Laughter echoing ]

18:42.580 --> 18:46.426
[ Music continues]

18:48.919 --> 18:52.093
MAN ON LOUDSPEAKER: Prisoners
at the bar, how do you plead?

18:52.214 --> 18:55.593
- Guilty!
'[ Laughter ]

18:55.718 --> 18:57.720
[ Music continues]

18:57.845 --> 18:59.472
What are you laughing at?!

18:59.597 --> 19:01.816
[ Laughter continues]

19:15.363 --> 19:17.866
[ Music continues]

19:41.514 --> 19:44.393
[ Down-tempo music playing ]

19:49.689 --> 19:50.861
Blore.

19:51.357 --> 19:54.406
Watch them.

19:57.405 --> 19:59.874
You stick with me, Vera.

19:59.990 --> 20:01.992
We're gonna get through this.

20:04.036 --> 20:06.755
I have no intention
of getting killed.

20:10.334 --> 20:14.805
Death...is for other people,
not for us.

20:18.467 --> 20:20.595
DR. ARMSTRONG:
[Whispering ] You see?

20:20.720 --> 20:23.473
Look at them.
Together.

20:24.849 --> 20:26.692
Perhaps it's them.

20:27.518 --> 20:29.520
Mr. and Mrs. Owen.

20:30.813 --> 20:36.866
It's them.

20:38.696 --> 20:39.868
Fine.

20:42.366 --> 20:44.209
Why am I wearing
this fucking hat'?

20:44.326 --> 20:45.873
[ Music continues]

20:45.995 --> 20:47.963
I'm going to bed.

20:48.748 --> 20:50.750
This party's over.

21:07.099 --> 21:09.272
[ Music stops]

21:09.393 --> 21:12.442
[Thunder rumbling ]

22:13.624 --> 22:15.626
[ Latch clicks]

22:44.989 --> 22:46.662
[ Exhales deeply]

23:02.590 --> 23:04.763
[ Breathing heavily]

23:12.558 --> 23:15.778
BLORE: Now, look here, sunshine.
You've been pinched.

23:15.895 --> 23:18.239
And we know what for.

23:18.355 --> 23:22.656
Lurking about in a gentleman's
public convenience, in the bogs.

23:22.776 --> 23:25.825
What am I, born yesterday?

23:25.946 --> 23:29.667
Now, you're lucky you got me,
not some other copper

23:29.783 --> 23:32.707
who might have been
a bit heavy-handed.

23:32.828 --> 23:34.626
I mean...look at you.

23:34.747 --> 23:36.795
There's nothing of you.

23:36.916 --> 23:39.135
You're soft.

23:39.251 --> 23:40.628
- Eh?
-[ Chuckles softly]

23:40.753 --> 23:43.597
Like a peach or something.

23:44.089 --> 23:47.013
You'd be mush in a moment.

23:47.134 --> 23:49.683
[ Exhales deeply]
So go on.

23:50.721 --> 23:52.268
On your way.

23:53.641 --> 23:56.269
And let this be a lesson to you,
all right?

23:56.393 --> 23:58.566
Be more discreet.

23:58.687 --> 24:00.405
You don't want to end up
getting a bloody nose

24:00.522 --> 24:01.648
or doing a stretch inside,

24:01.774 --> 24:04.277
'cause it's no fun for you lot
in the nick.

24:05.027 --> 24:07.029
Go on.
Scarper.

24:09.865 --> 24:11.367
Thank you.

24:17.164 --> 24:19.667
That's what I should've done,
isn't it?

24:21.001 --> 24:23.095
That's what I should've done.

24:25.297 --> 24:27.140
But I didn't.

24:29.093 --> 24:31.187
[Grunts]

24:35.933 --> 24:37.355
[ Exhales deeply]

24:37.476 --> 24:39.979
[Wind whistling]

24:55.202 --> 24:57.204
[ Hinges creak]

25:00.541 --> 25:03.090
[ Door closes]

25:03.210 --> 25:05.212
[ Footsteps]

25:26.984 --> 25:28.907
Bastard.

25:31.905 --> 25:34.078
[Whispering]
Lombard. Lombard.

25:34.199 --> 25:35.451
Lombard!
Lombard!

25:35.576 --> 25:37.920
[ Banging on door]

25:38.037 --> 25:38.959
Eh!

25:42.916 --> 25:44.589
VERA:
What is it?

25:44.710 --> 25:47.463
It's him.
It is Armstrong.

25:47.588 --> 25:49.761
He's left the house.
I saw him.

25:51.175 --> 25:54.805
Lock your door, Vera,
and put a chair against it.

25:54.928 --> 25:57.431
[Thunder crashes]

26:33.342 --> 26:34.844
How are you?

26:36.637 --> 26:38.184
How is Mrs. Hamilton?

26:38.305 --> 26:40.603
I'm taking her to London.

26:40.724 --> 26:42.067
She can't stay here.

26:42.643 --> 26:44.361
Of course.

26:45.771 --> 26:49.401
She, uh, wants to give you
three months' pay

26:49.525 --> 26:52.574
in lieu of notice because,
obviously,

26:52.694 --> 26:56.415
you cannot be a governess when
there is no child to govern.

26:57.616 --> 27:02.372
If Mrs. Hamilton is in London,
I can look after the house.

27:03.705 --> 27:05.173
Even if I'm not governess,

27:05.290 --> 27:07.133
I can still look after
the house.

27:07.251 --> 27:08.298
As a friend.

27:08.418 --> 27:10.261
I'm locking the house up.

27:11.088 --> 27:12.840
I imagine it might be sold.

27:14.550 --> 27:17.053
But it's yours now.

27:22.724 --> 27:25.728
I will have to find somewhere
to stay.

27:26.603 --> 27:28.731
I'll find a nice hotel.

27:29.898 --> 27:31.696
For when you come down.

27:31.817 --> 27:34.411
Perhaps I'll find us
a little cottage.

27:34.528 --> 27:36.530
I have to be with Olivia.

27:37.197 --> 27:39.541
She's really rather unwell.

27:40.159 --> 27:42.253
There will be an inquest.

27:43.203 --> 27:46.798
They want it to be quite soon,
so you'll be needed.

27:46.915 --> 27:48.542
Of course.

27:50.085 --> 27:52.008
And you'll come down for that?

27:54.715 --> 27:56.183
I have to go.

27:58.594 --> 28:00.688
Poor little Cyril.

28:05.559 --> 28:07.402
Poor little Cyril.

28:19.198 --> 28:22.202
[ Birds chirping in distance]

28:26.288 --> 28:29.758
[ Door opens, closes,
footsteps approaching ]

28:29.875 --> 28:32.048
[ Knock on door]

28:32.169 --> 28:34.888
PHILIP:
Vera. It's us.

29:11.250 --> 29:13.969
BLORE:
It was just on your bed.

29:14.086 --> 29:17.590
It was just on my bed.

29:17.714 --> 29:20.137
Well, how do I know you didn't
plant it in there last night?

29:20.259 --> 29:21.886
Because if Philip had the gun
before now,

29:22.010 --> 29:23.227
he would have
taken it with you

29:23.345 --> 29:24.938
when you went after Armstrong,
wouldn't he?

29:25.055 --> 29:27.183
Well, you could have crept out
of your room and planted it.

29:27.307 --> 29:28.980
There was no one 'round here
to hear you.

29:29.101 --> 29:31.195
I had my door locked
in case Armstrong came back.

29:31.311 --> 29:33.279
Armstrong's disappeared.

29:33.397 --> 29:35.115
Thin air.

29:35.232 --> 29:38.702
We split up when we went
searching last night, didn't we?

29:38.819 --> 29:40.196
Yes, we did.

29:40.320 --> 29:41.617
Did you find him?

29:41.738 --> 29:43.081
You chuck him off the cliff?

29:43.198 --> 29:46.498
No, Tubs, I didn't find him and
chuck him off the cliff.

29:46.618 --> 29:48.495
-Did you?
-No!

29:49.413 --> 29:50.665
No.

29:51.248 --> 29:53.250
VERA:
Red herring.

29:54.001 --> 29:54.968
What?

29:55.085 --> 29:58.089
“Four little soldier boys
going out to sea.

29:58.213 --> 30:01.592
A red herring swallowed one,
and then there were three."

30:01.717 --> 30:03.344
Red herring.

30:03.468 --> 30:05.596
Armstrong's still alive.

30:05.721 --> 30:09.351
Why is it always you
that works it out?

30:10.434 --> 30:13.404
Has been from the off, isn't it?

30:14.021 --> 30:15.648
Working it out.

30:15.772 --> 30:18.241
Armstrong said that and all.

30:18.358 --> 30:20.577
PHILIP:
It's been a long night.

30:21.153 --> 30:23.372
You're letting the booze
and the powder

30:23.488 --> 30:25.035
do the thinking for you, Tubs.

30:25.157 --> 30:26.909
I told you
to stop calling me that.

30:30.037 --> 30:32.916
Your first name's William,
isn't it?

30:33.040 --> 30:35.168
Do you get Will <i>or...</i>

30:35.292 --> 30:37.169
Bill.

30:37.294 --> 30:38.967
I get Bill.

30:39.463 --> 30:44.390
Well, Bill...whose idea was it
to put music on,

30:44.509 --> 30:48.104
to get drunk so we'd all
pass out and not hear anything?

30:49.264 --> 30:50.436
Armstrong.

30:50.557 --> 30:53.652
And who did you first suspect?

30:54.853 --> 30:57.777
Who did you get the scent on,
right from the off?

31:00.192 --> 31:01.910
Armstrong.

31:02.986 --> 31:04.659
VERA:
Red herring.

31:05.238 --> 31:07.912
He's been playing us
off each other from the start.

31:08.617 --> 31:09.743
And he's still alive.

31:09.868 --> 31:12.041
Because people don't
just vanish --

31:12.162 --> 31:14.130
not on an island this size.

31:14.247 --> 31:16.249
He's still alive.

31:20.212 --> 31:23.466
BLORE:
I've got an allotment at home.

31:24.716 --> 31:25.842
In Edmonton.

31:28.178 --> 31:29.600
I love it.

31:30.180 --> 31:33.104
It's my little patch
of paradise.

31:34.142 --> 31:35.644
That's the best thing
in the world,

31:35.769 --> 31:41.401
just sitting there,
watching it all...growing away.

31:43.902 --> 31:45.495
Cup of tea from the flask

31:45.612 --> 31:47.455
and a bit of bread
and a bit of cheese

31:47.572 --> 31:54.046
and a...radish that you pulled
from the ground a moment before.

31:54.746 --> 31:56.464
Great big peppery radish.

32:02.379 --> 32:04.256
Simple things.

32:05.799 --> 32:07.392
Good things.

32:11.221 --> 32:14.976
I wish I'd chucked that letter
from Ulick Norman Owen

32:15.100 --> 32:16.443
in the bin.

32:18.603 --> 32:20.947
And it serves me right.

32:21.565 --> 32:25.286
Trying to earn a bit of cash
on the sly.

32:25.402 --> 32:27.575
Serves us all right.

32:29.489 --> 32:31.662
[ Lighter clicks]

32:31.783 --> 32:33.956
Are we dead already?

32:34.995 --> 32:36.372
What?

32:37.372 --> 32:40.967
Perhaps we're dead already
and we just don't realize it...

32:42.043 --> 32:43.841
...and this is hell.

32:45.172 --> 32:46.890
We're in hell.

32:47.424 --> 32:50.598
And we're being punished
for what we done.

32:52.888 --> 32:54.982
[Voice breaking ]
'Cause I did kill him.

32:56.558 --> 32:58.060
Landon

33:00.479 --> 33:03.949
I stomped him till he was pulp.

33:05.108 --> 33:07.952
His own mother couldn't see him.

33:08.069 --> 33:09.787
Couldn't say goodbye.

33:12.282 --> 33:14.956
I murdered him, all right.

33:16.745 --> 33:21.546
He was helpless,
and I-l didn't stop.

33:22.959 --> 33:25.303
Must have been so frightened.

33:27.464 --> 33:29.216
Just a young lad.

33:29.341 --> 33:31.309
[ Sobs ]

33:32.511 --> 33:34.730
I've got a tomato crop
that's got to be harvested.

33:34.846 --> 33:36.189
Who's gonna do that?

33:36.306 --> 33:38.934
Who's -- What's gonna happen
to my allotment?

33:39.059 --> 33:41.983
PHILIP:
Hey. Hey, come on, Tubs.

33:42.103 --> 33:44.105
We're not done yet.

33:44.689 --> 33:47.238
It's us three against him.
We can hold our own.

33:47.359 --> 33:48.906
VERA: And someone has to come
for us soon.

33:49.027 --> 33:50.779
- They -- They have to.
- PHILIP: Mm-hmm.

33:50.904 --> 33:52.372
That's the spirit.

33:52.489 --> 33:54.162
BLORE:
Who's gonna come for us?

33:55.534 --> 33:59.289
That Narracott never turned up
when he was supposed to.

34:00.163 --> 34:01.836
Reckon he was paid off.

34:01.957 --> 34:05.006
We light a fire on the cliff.

34:05.126 --> 34:06.298
Someone's bound to see it.

34:06.419 --> 34:08.967
VERA: Okay.
We're going to need supplies.

34:09.089 --> 34:10.762
I don't want to spend
another night in this house.

34:10.882 --> 34:12.350
Do you?

34:12.467 --> 34:15.437
I reckon we're being watched.

34:18.681 --> 34:19.728
We are.

34:25.397 --> 34:27.399
[ Rattling ]

34:47.585 --> 34:49.384
- PHILIP: Let's go.
- VERA: Okay.

34:50.714 --> 34:52.216
Come on, Tubs.
Let's go.

35:08.940 --> 35:11.113
[ Footsteps approaching ]

35:28.418 --> 35:30.420
[ Door closes]

35:31.546 --> 35:34.049
[ Birds crying ]

35:38.136 --> 35:39.683
[ Metal clatters]

35:39.804 --> 35:41.272
[ Lighter clicks]

35:44.768 --> 35:45.860
Where is he?

35:53.735 --> 35:55.078
Stay here.

35:56.946 --> 35:58.789
Don't follow me.

36:16.049 --> 36:19.644
[Growling]

36:36.861 --> 36:37.828
Oh.

36:37.946 --> 36:40.119
[ Breathing heavily]

36:49.040 --> 36:53.341
“Three little soldier boys
walking in the zoo.

36:53.461 --> 36:56.260
A big bear hugged one,
and then there were two.“

36:57.424 --> 37:00.428
PHILIP:
Poor Tubs.

37:00.552 --> 37:02.896
Poor Tubs.

37:06.391 --> 37:07.608
[ Door opens, closes]

37:07.726 --> 37:10.195
[Clock chiming]

37:32.000 --> 37:34.298
[ Breathing heavily]

37:36.463 --> 37:38.966
[Wind whistling]

37:42.844 --> 37:45.097
The 'side's changing.

37:49.017 --> 37:50.018
Philip?

37:51.936 --> 37:53.779
Philip.

37:53.897 --> 37:55.899
There's something down there.

38:57.836 --> 38:59.838
PHILIP:
Armstrong.

39:16.312 --> 39:17.529
Come on.

39:17.647 --> 39:18.614
Where?

39:18.731 --> 39:20.358
Not here.

39:20.942 --> 39:22.740
I need to find a better view.

39:23.570 --> 39:24.446
No, no, no.

39:24.571 --> 39:26.414
We -- We can't leave him
like this.

39:26.531 --> 39:28.499
It's not right.
We can't leave him.

39:28.616 --> 39:30.084
- Yes, we can.
- No.

39:30.201 --> 39:32.829
When the boat comes, Philip,
they'll see him like this,

39:32.954 --> 39:36.458
and we haven't done the decent,
the -- the right thing.

39:36.583 --> 39:38.256
How will it look for us?

39:39.043 --> 39:40.716
Please.

39:41.838 --> 39:43.215
Please!

39:59.147 --> 40:01.149
[Grunts]

40:13.620 --> 40:15.588
It's you.

40:15.705 --> 40:18.424
It's you.
It's all you, all of it.

40:18.541 --> 40:19.508
Give me the gun.

40:19.626 --> 40:21.424
You're going to kill me.

40:21.544 --> 40:23.797
No.

40:24.839 --> 40:27.683
I'm not gonna kill you, Vera.

40:27.800 --> 40:29.177
But there's somebody else
on this island --

40:29.302 --> 40:30.178
There's no one else!

40:30.303 --> 40:32.397
There's somebody on this island,
and they're gonna kill us both

40:32.513 --> 40:33.730
if you don't give me that gun.

40:33.848 --> 40:35.566
There's no one else!
You've killed them all!

40:35.683 --> 40:38.152
Listen to me.
We're being hunted!

40:38.269 --> 40:40.772
Right now we're being hunted!

40:42.023 --> 40:43.525
I need the gun!

40:46.694 --> 40:48.287
Give it to me.

40:52.033 --> 40:53.205
Vera.

40:59.332 --> 41:00.959
Give me the gun.

41:04.545 --> 41:06.513
Give me the gun, Vera.

41:18.434 --> 41:19.777
-[ Grunts ]
-[ Gunshot ]

41:19.894 --> 41:21.862
[Grunts]

41:26.234 --> 41:28.407
[Gunshot]

41:33.116 --> 41:35.210
[ Screaming ]

41:58.725 --> 42:04.323
VERA: I promised him a game of
bat and ball after our lessons.

42:05.064 --> 42:07.783
A reward for being so good.

42:09.944 --> 42:11.912
He wanted to swim.

42:12.405 --> 42:14.783
He always wanted to swim.

42:14.907 --> 42:16.750
But I said no.

42:18.619 --> 42:22.874
I went to get the bat and ball
for our game...

42:22.999 --> 42:25.001
and he was gone.

42:25.960 --> 42:27.962
I ran after him.

42:28.087 --> 42:30.385
I ran as fast <i>as</i> I could.

42:31.299 --> 42:33.518
If only I hadn't turned away
for a minute,

42:33.634 --> 42:36.808
but it was only a minute
while I got the bat and ball.

42:37.555 --> 42:39.478
If only...

42:46.397 --> 42:48.491
[ Exhales deeply]

42:53.154 --> 42:54.622
Thank you.

42:54.739 --> 42:57.913
Thank you for trying to save
him.

42:59.035 --> 43:00.287
Thank you for trying.

43:00.870 --> 43:01.837
<i>Oh, God.</i>

43:01.954 --> 43:04.082
[ Crying ]
Oh, God.

43:15.551 --> 43:17.303
You know, before I wasn't sure.

43:20.515 --> 43:22.313
But I am sure now.

43:22.433 --> 43:25.528
Watching you, hearing you speak.

43:25.645 --> 43:27.318
Now I'm sure.

43:27.855 --> 43:30.449
- What are you sure of?
- That you're lying.

43:33.611 --> 43:36.706
You couldn't catch up with...
Cyril?

43:37.448 --> 43:39.826
I've seen you run, Vera.

43:39.951 --> 43:41.999
You're fast.
You're strong.

43:42.120 --> 43:43.087
You sprint.

43:43.204 --> 43:44.581
You turn your back for a moment

43:44.705 --> 43:46.127
and you couldn't catch up
with Cyril?

43:46.249 --> 43:49.423
- Hugo, you can't think this.
- I know why you did it.

43:49.544 --> 43:52.423
But what you don't understand is
I really loved that little boy.

43:52.547 --> 43:54.094
So did I.

43:54.215 --> 43:55.467
And I love you.

43:58.344 --> 43:59.721
I can't prove it.

43:59.846 --> 44:00.972
I can't prove a thing.

44:01.097 --> 44:04.897
Oh, but, Vera,
if I did have proof...

44:05.017 --> 44:06.485
I'd see you hang.

44:18.865 --> 44:20.993
Cyril!

44:21.117 --> 44:23.620
[ Down-tempo music playing ]

45:13.002 --> 45:14.675
Now...

45:17.506 --> 45:20.180
You're strong enough to swim
to that rock, aren't you?

45:20.301 --> 45:22.224
You're strong enough.

45:22.428 --> 45:23.429
Excited?

45:24.680 --> 45:25.977
Okay.

45:26.098 --> 45:27.771
On your marks.

45:27.892 --> 45:29.815
Get set.

45:29.936 --> 45:31.153
Go!

46:31.747 --> 46:34.796
[Shouting in distance]

46:36.210 --> 46:38.429
MAN: [ Echoing ]
Nearly there!

46:39.797 --> 46:41.515
Don't worry!

46:42.300 --> 46:44.473
Hold on!

46:48.347 --> 46:49.894
Don't worry.

46:50.016 --> 46:52.735
I've got you.

48:09.970 --> 48:12.689
[Clock ticking ]

48:24.735 --> 48:27.238
[Thunder rumbles]

50:10.216 --> 50:12.389
[ Footsteps]

50:20.226 --> 50:21.773
[ Latch clicks]

50:23.562 --> 50:25.280
VERA:
Hugo.

50:26.023 --> 50:27.946
Hugo.

50:28.067 --> 50:30.069
[ Hinges creaking ]

50:38.702 --> 50:40.579
[ Gasping ]

50:46.085 --> 50:49.430
“Two little soldier boys
sitting in the sun."

50:49.547 --> 50:51.140
[ Gasping ]

50:51.257 --> 50:55.433
"One got frizzled up,
and then there was one.“

50:58.180 --> 51:02.606
“One little soldier boy left
all alone.

51:02.726 --> 51:07.197
He went and hanged himself...
and then there were none."

51:10.359 --> 51:12.236
You wondering about that...

51:12.361 --> 51:14.363
[ Chuckles ]

51:15.406 --> 51:17.955
Liver and kidneys.

51:18.075 --> 51:21.329
You all believed the doctor
when he said I was dead.

51:21.453 --> 51:22.454
None of you checked.

51:22.580 --> 51:23.797
I need to get down.

51:23.914 --> 51:26.667
Armstrong made it
so much easier.

51:27.751 --> 51:31.176
He was very keen
to forge an alliance.

51:31.922 --> 51:33.845
I don't know what he thought
was going to happen

51:33.966 --> 51:36.344
when he ran out into the night
to meet me.

51:36.468 --> 51:38.436
Perhaps that I was going to
save him.

51:38.554 --> 51:40.101
[ Gasping ]

51:40.222 --> 51:43.647
I lied about the success
of my surgery.

51:45.227 --> 51:48.857
The mass --
The tumor is spreading.

51:48.981 --> 51:53.282
There's nothing to be done
but await the inevitable.

51:53.861 --> 51:56.580
It's quite extraordinarily
painful.

51:58.532 --> 52:01.536
Well, not long now, though, hmm?

52:01.660 --> 52:03.287
Why are you doing this?

52:03.412 --> 52:06.165
Because justice comes to all.

52:07.333 --> 52:09.506
I told you that.
Were you not listening?

52:10.419 --> 52:13.263
The evidence that led me
to convict Edward Seton

52:13.380 --> 52:16.554
was considered too terrible
to be made public.

52:18.510 --> 52:20.558
It was the stuff of nightmares.

52:21.555 --> 52:23.057
Really.

52:24.475 --> 52:27.103
And where others were
revolted...

52:29.938 --> 52:32.441
...Miss Claythorne,
I was fascinated.

52:35.110 --> 52:37.954
And when Seton looked
into my eyes,

52:38.072 --> 52:40.495
he could see
that I was thrilled.

52:41.408 --> 52:44.127
He knew that I was
a kindred spirit.

52:46.246 --> 52:48.294
And when his neck snapped,

52:50.042 --> 52:52.716
...l felt as if I had been
handed a gift.

52:52.836 --> 52:53.928
No.

52:54.046 --> 52:55.923
No.
[ Gasps ]

52:56.048 --> 52:58.267
You don't mean any of this.

52:58.384 --> 53:00.557
You are a good man.

53:00.678 --> 53:01.804
Moral.

53:01.929 --> 53:03.681
- Moral?
-[ Grunts ]

53:06.100 --> 53:08.478
Maybe there's something in that.

53:08.602 --> 53:12.732
There are differences
between Seton and myself.

53:12.856 --> 53:15.359
All his victims were innocent.

53:16.944 --> 53:18.992
You are all guilty.

53:20.906 --> 53:22.499
Now, imagine.

53:22.616 --> 53:26.587
The detectives arrive to find
a house full of slaughter

53:26.704 --> 53:30.584
and the handiwork
of U.N. Owen everywhere.

53:31.750 --> 53:32.626
[Sighs]

53:32.751 --> 53:36.346
But U.N. Owen himself
is nowhere to be seen.

53:36.463 --> 53:38.716
But who else could have fired
the final shot

53:38.841 --> 53:43.062
that ended the life
of the unimpeachable judge?

53:45.139 --> 53:47.608
Ten bodies and no murderer.

53:47.725 --> 53:49.272
[ Gasps ]

53:49.393 --> 53:51.270
How could he have disappeared?

53:51.395 --> 53:53.489
[Gags]

53:54.189 --> 53:57.693
It's so unfathomable.

53:58.944 --> 54:02.323
They'll be worrying about it
for years.

54:02.906 --> 54:04.203
No.

54:04.324 --> 54:05.541
No.
Wait.

54:05.659 --> 54:07.582
There's -- There's no...

54:07.703 --> 54:10.001
There's no more bullets.

54:10.122 --> 54:15.219
There -- There can be no final
shot because the gun is empty.

54:15.335 --> 54:17.463
There are no more bullets.

54:18.547 --> 54:20.049
Damn.

54:20.758 --> 54:22.180
It's all spoiled.

54:22.760 --> 54:24.728
- No, it's not spoiled.
- Yes, it is.

54:24.845 --> 54:26.893
There are corpses everywhere
and only me left.

54:27.014 --> 54:28.311
Not just you.

54:28.432 --> 54:30.150
There's me.

54:30.267 --> 54:33.567
The two of us, together.

54:33.687 --> 54:34.939
[Gulps]

54:35.063 --> 54:37.566
We'll --
We'll say it was Philip,

54:37.691 --> 54:38.783
that he was mad.

54:38.901 --> 54:41.871
Oh, he was quite the sanest
of the lot, I thought.

54:41.987 --> 54:43.864
He was insane.

54:45.032 --> 54:48.286
He killed us all,
and I shot him.

54:49.077 --> 54:51.876
I shot him to defend us.

54:52.414 --> 54:54.291
It was all Philip Lombard.

54:56.418 --> 54:58.295
You took him as your lover.

54:58.420 --> 54:59.922
Yes.

55:00.631 --> 55:02.178
Got his blood on your feet.

55:02.299 --> 55:03.767
Self-defense.

55:04.426 --> 55:06.099
We'll say that.

55:07.346 --> 55:08.723
We'll say that.

55:08.847 --> 55:10.645
They'll believe us.

55:10.766 --> 55:12.643
They believed me last time.

55:12.768 --> 55:14.111
[ Gasps ]

55:19.024 --> 55:22.278
What a beguiling woman you are,
Miss Claythorne.

55:23.612 --> 55:25.034
Vera.

55:27.991 --> 55:29.993
Quite my favorite, really.

55:31.912 --> 55:34.665
There's no final bullet, Judge.

55:35.499 --> 55:36.967
But I can save us both.

55:37.543 --> 55:39.136
[ Inhales sharply]

55:39.253 --> 55:43.554
I'll keep your secret,
and I will save us both.

55:44.049 --> 55:45.517
Just let me down.

55:45.634 --> 55:46.977
Please.

55:49.972 --> 55:51.315
[ Rope creaking ]

55:51.431 --> 55:53.559
[Gagging]

56:05.028 --> 56:08.032
You forgot the one that shot me.

56:11.535 --> 56:13.537
[Gagging]

